## 2. Privacy Audit — Before We Touch the Data

ShopSmart's loyalty program collects a wide range of data. Before building any model, we apply a **GDPR data minimisation check**: does each feature contribute meaningfully to churn prediction, and is it proportionate to use it?

| Feature | Privacy Risk | Decision | Reason |
|---------|-------------|---------|--------|
| Tenure (months in program) | 🟢 Low | ✅ Use | Aggregated, no PII |
| Order count (last 6 months) | 🟢 Low | ✅ Use | Behavioural aggregate |
| Days since last order | 🟢 Low | ✅ Use | Recency signal |
| Satisfaction score | 🟢 Low | ✅ Use | Self-reported |
| Coupon usage rate | 🟢 Low | ✅ Use | Ratio, not transaction detail |
| City tier | 🟢 Low | ✅ Use | Regional, not address |
| Device type | 🟡 Medium | ✅ Use | Aggregate only, no device ID |
| Preferred order category | 🟢 Low | ✅ Use | Category-level, not items |
| Individual transactions | 🔴 High | ❌ Exclude | Violates data minimisation |
| Browsing/click history | 🔴 High | ❌ Exclude | Disproportionate to purpose |
| Login timestamps | 🔴 High | ❌ Exclude | Not needed for churn prediction |

✅ **We proceed with only privacy-safe features.** This is a real-world constraint that most Kaggle notebooks ignore — and it's what makes this analysis relevant to actual CRM practice.
